article.description:
Adrienne Goodson and LaToya Thomas each had
22 points to help the San Antonio Silver Stars beat Charlotte 82-65 on Friday night, preventing the Sting from clinching a playoff spot.
article.headline: Sting, Shock tied for East's final spot
article.linkText: That Stings: Silver Stars keep Charlotte from clinching
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- The San Antonio Silver Stars used their last
game of the season to finally put it all together.

Adrienne Goodson and LaToya Thomas each had 22 points to help
the Silver Stars beat Charlotte 82-65 on Friday night, preventing
the Sting from clinching a playoff spot.

The Sting (16-17) dropped into a tie with the Detroit Shock for
the final playoff spot in the Eastern Conference. The two teams
meet Sunday in a virtual playoff game in Detroit, with the winner
going to the postseason.

The Washington Mystics and New York Liberty locked up playoff
spots with victories Friday night. The Connecticut Sun clinched a
spot on Wednesday.

"We just didn't get it done tonight," said guard Dawn Staley.
"It was a very difficult loss. We're still in the position to
(make the playoffs), but I just hope we take care of business on
Sunday."

San Antonio finished the season 9-25, the second-worst record in
franchise history. They were 7-21 in 1997.

The Silver Stars used a 21-7 run midway through the second half
to break open a close game. Thomas had 12 points during the run,
capping it with a three-point play with eight minutes remaining.

San Antonio's Semeka Randall, who announced her retirement
before the game, set a franchise record for steals in a game with
eight.

"It was a better effort, not just by (Semeka), but the team as
well," said head coach Shell Dailey. "They just put it all
together tonight and had fun. Charlotte needed this game and we
played well."

Shannon Johnson had 16 points and seven assists for the Silver
Stars, going 5-of-8 from the field and perfect from the 3-point
line (2-for-2) and free throw line (4-for-4).

The Sting have struggled on the road of late, going 2-9 in their
last 11.

Charlotte Smith-Taylor led the Sting with 14 points, while
Allison Feaster had 12. Staley scored 11 and tied a season high
with 10 assists.

Feaster hit a 19-foot jumper as time expired in the first half
to send both teams into the locker room tied at 28.

Charlotte took a lead early in the second half when Tammy
Sutton-Brown's layup made it 32-31, but that was the Sting's last
lead of the night.

The Silver Stars shot 86 percent from the free-throw line, going
18-for-21.
